g.text: Cuno: The boy breathes on the glass and writes something on the fogged up surface, then wipes it all away with his sleeve.
Cuno: "Shit I know this..." His voice is excited as he nods approvingly. "Cuno gets this shit. Ballistics shit, science shit."
Authority: He's used to knowing who to trust. This makes him uncomfortable.
Visual Calculus: A powerful gust of wind coming in from the bay rattles the windowpane.
Logic: The lead is flimsy, but *what else is there*? The alternative is going around Martinaise looking under every rock and talking to every person.
Visual Calculus: A vague sense of disappointment fills you. The glass shimmers as if taunting you with its secrets.

Kim Kitsuragi: "No. On the contrary, this whole room could be very useful if we could read it." He looks down the stairs. "Maybe later."
Clear Window: The window stands mute in the frame. The wind picks up outside.

Visual Calculus: 72%. With an antique weapon that fires military-grade ammunition -- a Belle-Magrave rifle, for example. This is a good short distance, but not too short. The perpetrator aimed with their back against the railing, or possibly kneeling for precision. This would explain why it only took them one shot.

Visual Calculus: The lights were on in here. Outside it was dark. It was like shooting fish in an aquarium -- a well lit aquarium. The victim opened his mouth to let the bullet in. Neither of them would have seen anything outside, in the darkness -- too busy with their own bodies.
